Use conditional compilation with `#if` directives in your `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each platform-specific implementation goes under `Platforms/<platform>/` and is only compiled for that target, so there's no risk of missing types on other platforms.

**Alternative** — if you prefer avoiding `#if` blocks, use partial classes or the **filename-based multi-targeting** convention (e.g., `NotificationService.android.cs`, `NotificationService.ios.cs`) and register a single concrete type:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, NotificationService>();
```

The build system picks the right file per platform automatically. This approach scales better as you add more platform services.
